card.name: README
card.desc:
This is where we track all hacknight projects through all phases -- from seed ideas right through to completion!

## How To Use

1. Log into Trello!
  - We recommend using your own account, but in a pinch, use these: xxxxxx / xxxxx
2. Create a project card.
  - We've created [a template card](https://trello.com/c/IQZfskte/41-template-project) that you can use a guide.
    - The card **title** is used for the project name.
    - The **description** is used to describe your project on the pitch board and website.
    - The **attachment fields** are specifically formatted to provide additional button links and images on the website. (The part before the colon is the part that must be consistent.)
    - The **labels** are used to tag your project with "asks" (things you need from contributors), "tools" (skills you can make use of), "scopes" (the region the projects bears immediate relevance to), and "project phase" (how far along it is).
    - The **members** assigned to the card will be the person(s) pitching the project.

## Notes

- Feel free to add more labels!

card.name: City of Toronto org chart (organogram)
card.desc:
Right now, there is no open dataset for the employees and org structure of City of Toronto. There is some prior art from gov.uk

Having the org chart in data form would allow it to be resurfaced in other ways, which could help citizens understand a bit of the complex structure of government.

- gov.uk organogram: [visualization](https://data.gov.uk/organogram/) [dataset](https://data.gov.uk/dataset/ff76be1f-4f37-4bef-beb7-32b259413be1/organogram-of-staff-roles-salaries) [data schema](https://github.com/datagovuk/schemas/tree/master/organogram)
- [List of PDF directories](https://www.toronto.ca/city-government/accountability-operations-customer-service/city-administration/staff-directory-divisions-and-customer-service/) of City of Toronto staff/departments
- A scraper I made for the PDF contact directory: [`patcon/toronto-contact-pdf-scraping`](https://github.com/patcon/toronto-contact-pdf-scraping)

## Opportunities

- contact open data team about discussing getting the data in machine-readable form
- improve scrapers to derive data from PDFs (will be brittle, and not quite as good)
- contact gov.uk team about open source code for visualization
  - port tool to work with city of toronto data

card.name: Digital Community-Bridging Team
card.desc:
## Challenge

Many local communities rely on digital communication tools like Slack. In many ways, Slack is amazing. But Slack is not as open as prior ways that communities interacted online, using tools built for open collaboration and discovery: bulletin boards, online forums, public mailing lists. With these tools, people not involved in projects could find records of happenings after the fact, and learn from them, if not participate.

In contrast, Slack was created to private company conversations, and it reflects that. Slack conversations and activities often get silo'd within the community of invited participants. Conversations can't easily be shared with other communities -- they must either register or be invited to see discussion.

Slack, while more user-friendly, is very different from previous modes of group communication online. Bulletin boards, online forums, and mailing lists are previous systems that were more open. 

## Idea

A project/team that organizes as a *single-purpose support team,* responding to requests to stitch together various digital communities through digital chat bridges

Possible activities might include:

- manage bridging infrastructure
- suggest patterns of using comms tools
  - example: Using bridges between Slack and other tools, to make conversations more public.
- make introductions between groups that might want to share digital space more freely through bridging

## Challenge

Many local communities rely on digital communication tools like Slack. In many ways, Slack is amazing. But Slack is not as open as prior ways that communities interacted online, using tools built for open collaboration and discovery: bulletin boards, online forums, public mailing lists. With these tools, people not involved in projects could find records of happenings after the fact, and learn from them, if not participate.

In contrast, Slack was created to private company conversations, and it reflects that. Slack conversations and activities often get silo'd within the community of invited participants. Conversations can't easily be shared with other communities -- they must either register or be invited to see discussion.

Slack, while more user-friendly, is very different from previous modes of group communication online. Bulletin boards, online forums, and mailing lists are previous systems that were more open. 

## Idea

A project/team that organizes as a *single-purpose support team,* responding to requests to stitch together various digital communities through digital chat bridges

Possible activities might include:

- manage bridging infrastructure
- suggest patterns for not being bound by comm tool limitations (ie. lack of public logs in slack, etc.)
- make introductions between groups that might want to share digital space more freely through bridging

Best bridge I've found is *Matterbridge*:
https://github.com/42wim/matterbridge

Here's @patcon's repo for posting it free on heroku:
https://github.com/edgi-govdata-archiving/matterbridge-heroku#readme

Screenshot: across many slacks: https://imgur.com/CqiPyeF
Screenshot: across chat platforms: https://imgur.com/oeH8SlD

card.name: "Parkdale days destroyed" gentrification indicator
card.desc:
Background: https://github.com/patcon/parkdale-days-destroyed#background

This project was a personal experiment that was never completed. Anyone is free to run with it if it's of interest to them. Value of project still needs to be validated with stakeholders (like perhaps Parkdale Community Land trust).

* Idea was discussed with Parkdale BIA, for which there didn't seem to be much interest.
* Premise was run by Mervyn Horgan, a socialogist who presented at an [event about gentrification in the Junction triangle](https://www.eventbrite.com/e/gentrification-in-the-junction-triangle-tickets-31820286333#): He said it might have merit, and [referred me to a few professions](https://gist.github.com/patcon/d7d8fd093ba6919c8e760c9aeaeb3642) for which practitioners might have more insight. However, I did not make time to followup.

Data: http://www1.toronto.ca/wps/portal/contentonly?vgnextoid=83a7c060155d0310VgnVCM1000003dd60f89RCRD&vgnextchannel=bee6e03bb8d1e310VgnVCM10000071d60f89RCRD

card.name: DemocracyXChange Summit
card.desc: Democracy thrives when citizens choose to actively participate in civic and political life to drive change. From citizens looking to advance the values of inclusivity, diversity and equality to neighbourhood groups coming together to shape the schools in their community, these large movements and small local campaigns all around the world are demonstrating the power of explicit engagement, technology, and new ways of organizing. DemocracyXChange is about the practical campaign skills and tools individuals and startup teams need to connect and make change happen. Come join us.

card.name: TTC Tracker
card.desc: Transit agencies are typically bad at communicating how good service is when service is good, and how bad service is when service is bad. Customers remember they're more salient experiences: the bad ones, without having a metric of how bad service was. Meanwhile, transit agencies' performance metrics do not reflect the customer experience, so we don't understand how what they are trying to improve upon affects our experience.

card.name: Free the Electorate
card.desc: Ontario election results are posted on the Elections Ontario website, but generally aren’t readily available outside election cycles, when the information is in the press. Poll-by-poll results are available as pdfs and spreadsheets back to 2007, and prior to that only basic election results are published online. We want to make this data more easily available by creating a set of standard documents and a database, as well as visualizations of that data for public use.

card.name: City of Brains
card.desc: The purpose of this project is to develop an understanding of how people access mental health services in Toronto, to share those stories to help others find their way to help, to identify common challenges in those stories, and then, design and develop technology solutions to support people in overcoming those challenges.

card.name: Toronto Councilmatic
card.desc: The purpose of this project is to create a beautiful citizen-controlled website that tracks all things related to City Council: the legislation introduced and passed, its various committees and the meetings they hold, and the councillors themselves.

card.name: Toronto Meshnet
card.desc: Meshnets are highly distributed, redundant intranet networks. A series of nodes, usually fashioned from cannibalized routers, emit signals that create a free self-contained and self-reliant network that’s accessible to any internet capable devices within range. We are dedicated to the growth of free-to-use wireless Internet access in Toronto’s public and publicly accessible spaces.

card.name: Budgetpedia
card.desc: The mission of this project is to support informed debate about the Toronto budget. Specifically, provide tools for activists to facilitate insight into the Toronto budget contents, provide ready access to annual budget process information, and more.

Get conversational data about who talks to who into a visualization that the CivicTechTO community can use to understand itself, and what sort of collaboration is happening.

card.desc:
[**GraphCommons**](https://graphcommons.com) is a platform for allowing artists and journalists to easily map network. This allows folks to easily understand relations and players in complex systems. The platform also allows the pieces of these maps to be shared, so that once someone maps a set of relationships, it can be imported and explored from other maps via their [Hub Explorer](https://blog.graphcommons.com/introducing-hub-explore/) -- maps share information.

Here's an example of a map: [Istanbul Creative Hubs](https://graphcommons.com/graphs/21cc69ad-86d7-489d-99ac-524a3aeb15b8?auto=true)

The idea is to **use the [Info-Go dataset](https://www.ontario.ca/data/government-ontario-employee-and-organization-directory-info-go) from the province of Ontario to map the org chart of the Ontario government in Graph Commons.**

Benefits of doing this include:

* easy update through GraphCommons ability to import CSVs
* other folks (journalists, citizens, gov employees) who are building other graphs could import and reference these nodes in their own maps (ie. this could be a reference map for others)
* it might help government employees understand their own organization
* it could be scripted to auto-update

old.desc:
Province of ON has INFO-GO ([data](https://www.ontario.ca/data/government-ontario-employee-and-organization-directory-info-go) and [directory](http://www.infogo.gov.on.ca/infogo/)).

Gov of Canada has GEDS ([data](http://open.canada.ca/data/en/dataset/8ec4a9df-b76b-4a67-8f93-cdbc2e040098) and [directory](http://sage-geds.tpsgc-pwgsc.gc.ca/en/GEDS/?pgid=012)).

City of Toronto has... [PDFs](). So many PDFs.

The information from these PDFs is apparently built from a few different places.

* Emails are not considered public by City, although they are by ONgov and CANgov. This might change, especially if there are positive case-studies for it being helpful.
* Phone numbers are public.
* Organizational structure (divisions, sections, units, subunits, etc.) are not machine readable, but that's a potential dataset.
* anecdotal evidence is that this information would be useful internally as well -- civil servants usually have to google their co-workers to find who they are in the big picture.

card.name: Open Source Smiley Terminal
card.desc:
City departments sometimes do surveys and released the data, like [Court Services did](http://www1.toronto.ca/wps/portal/contentonly?vgnextoid=9431ba0c10f85410VgnVCM10000071d60f89RCRD&vgnextchannel=0186e03bb8d1e310VgnVCM10000071d60f89RCRD) (to their great credit) in 2014.

But this data so far has been one-off, nor recurring. It is not possible to see improvements, nor trends, nor whether initial "issues" have improved. For citizens interested in contributing to citizen experience, and doing data-driven work, it would be wonderful to have a more consistent and empowering way to collect data on in-person experiences, which would be more likely to end up as open data.

It might be interesting to build a open version of the ["Smiley Terminal"](https://www.happy-or-not.com/en/measure/), a trademarked product. Then citizens could place it outside city areas where citizens are leaving after an interaction (waiting rooms, etc.). It could move around on rotation, and perhaps citizen groups could request that it be placed in certain places, or rent it for the day, or sponsor a campaign (perhaps longitudinal).

Might also be interesting to allow selecting a "mood", but then perhaps it prints out a receipt with QR code and link, so that more detailed data could be collected later, more at the leisure of the participant. (And perhaps also giving them time to reflect more on the interaction.)

card.name: "Parkdale days destroyed" gentrification indicator
card.desc:
Background: https://github.com/patcon/parkdale-days-destroyed#background

This project was a personal experiment that was never completed. Any is free to run with it if it's of interest to them. Value of project still needs to be validated with stakeholders (like perhaps Parkdale Community Land trust).

* Idea was discussed with Parkdale BIA, for which there didn't seem to be much interest.
* Premise was run by Mervyn Horgan, a socialogist who presented at an [event about gentrification in the Junction triangle](https://www.eventbrite.com/e/gentrification-in-the-junction-triangle-tickets-31820286333#): He said it might have merit, and [referred me to a few professions](https://gist.github.com/patcon/d7d8fd093ba6919c8e760c9aeaeb3642) for which practitioners might have more insight. However, I did not make time to followup.

cards.desc:
This is where we track all hacknight projects through all phases -- from seed ideas right through to completion!

## How To Use

1. Log into Trello!
  - We recommend using your own account, but in a pinch, use these: xxxxxx / xxxxx
2. Create a project card.
  - We've created [a template card](https://trello.com/c/IQZfskte/41-template-project) that you can use a guide.
    - The card **title** is used for the project name.
    - The **description** is used to describe your project on the pitch board and website.
    - The **attachment fields** are specifically formatted to provide additional button links and images on the website. (The part before the colon is the part that must be consistent.)
    - The **labels** are used to tag your project with "asks" (things you need from contributors), "tools" (skills you can make use of), "scopes" (the region the projects bears immediate relevance to), and "project phase" (how far along it is).
    - The **members** assigned to the card will be the person(s) pitching the project.

## Notes

- Feel free to add more labels!

cards.desc:
## Challenge

Many local communities rely on digital communication tools like Slack. In many ways, Slack is amazing. But Slack is not as open as prior ways that communities interacted online, using tools built for open collaboration and discovery: bulletin boards, online forums, public mailing lists. With these tools, people not involved in projects could find records of happenings after the fact, and learn from them, if not participate.

In contrast, Slack was created to private company conversations, and it reflects that. Slack conversations and activities often get silo'd within the community of invited participants. Conversations can't easily be shared with other communities -- they must either register or be invited to see discussion.

Slack, while more user-friendly, is very different from previous modes of group communication online. Bulletin boards, online forums, and mailing lists are previous systems that were more open. 

## Idea

A project/team that organizes as a *single-purpose support team,* responding to requests to stitch together various digital communities through digital chat bridges

Possible activities might include:

- manage bridging infrastructure
- suggest patterns of using comms tools
  - example: Using bridges between Slack and other tools, to make conversations more public.
- make introductions between groups that might want to share digital space more freely through bridging
cards.name: Digital Community-Bridging Team

cards.desc:
Right now, there is no open dataset for the employees and org structure of City of Toronto. There is some prior art from gov.uk

Having the org chart in data form would allow it to be resurfaced in other ways, which could help citizens understand a bit of the complex structure of government.

- gov.uk organogram: [visualization](https://data.gov.uk/organogram/) [dataset](https://data.gov.uk/dataset/ff76be1f-4f37-4bef-beb7-32b259413be1/organogram-of-staff-roles-salaries) [data schema](https://github.com/datagovuk/schemas/tree/master/organogram)
- [List of PDF directories](https://www.toronto.ca/city-government/accountability-operations-customer-service/city-administration/staff-directory-divisions-and-customer-service/) of City of Toronto staff/departments
- A scraper I made for the PDF contact directory: [`patcon/toronto-contact-pdf-scraping`](https://github.com/patcon/toronto-contact-pdf-scraping)

## Opportunities

- contact open data team about discussing getting the data in machine-readable form
- improve scrapers to derive data from PDFs (will be brittle, and not quite as good)
- contact gov.uk team about open source code for visualization
  - port tool to work with city of toronto data

members.bio:
I'm a bot designed to make Trello boards open for anyone to enter.

_by [Websites for Trello](http://websitesfortrello.com/)_

![demo image](http://i.imgur.com/VDK6nQI.gif)

If you have a board where you want to let anyone enter, to comment and see and all that, just create a card, name it in any way you want (it can be something like "Welcome to this board, please comment here to enter!") and add me to that card.

Every Trello user who leaves a comment in that card will be automatically addded as a "normal" member to the board.

### Demo

[Here's a board](https://trello.com/b/r2lSYIzl/welcome-to-this-board) where you can see me in action: https://trello.com/c/C2P7lM8A/1-you-can-be-a-member-of-this-board-if-you-want-just-comment-here

---

## About me

I'm a creation of the folks behind http://websitesfortrello.com/. You can find other helpful bots in http://websitesfortrello.com/trello-bots/
